Using the NBA API in R

news
code
analysis
Author

Patrick Coyle

Published

April 23, 2023

nba_api is a Python client for accessing data from www.nba.com. This post presents an example of using nba_api to create a data viz. This example begins by using reticulate::import() to import nba_api. Before doing this, we must:

  1. Install Python and configure R to use Python using the reticulate package;

  2. Install nba_api in Python.

A minimal working example for this setup would be useful. I do not have one, because my process involved the Anaconda GUI and so it is not reproducible.

For data viz, we use the nbaplotR package, which provides a ggplot2 geom for plotting NBA and WNBA logos. This package is not available on CRAN â€“ the developer recommends installing from Github using pak::pak():

if (!require("pak")) install.packages("pak")
pak::pak("mrcaseb/nbaplotR")
# Load R packages and Python modules ------
library(reticulate)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(ggiraph)
library(nbaplotR)
nba_api <- reticulate::import("nba_api")
LeagueDashTeamStats <- nba_api$stats$endpoints$leaguedashteamstats$LeagueDashTeamStats

# Pull and wrangle data from nba.com ------
my_df1 <- LeagueDashTeamStats(
  season = '2022-23',
  season_type_all_star = 'Regular Season'
)$get_data_frames()[[1]] %>% 
  mutate(
    TEAM_ABBR = valid_team_names("NBA")[c(1, 3, 2, 4:25, 27, 26, 28:30)]
  )

# Plot data ------
my_ggobj <- my_df1 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = REB, y = PTS)) +
  geom_nba_logos(
    aes(team_abbr = TEAM_ABBR), 
    width = 0.075,
    height = 0.075
  ) +
  theme_bw()
girafe(ggobj = my_ggobj)
